</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1359,1781]" pageId="4" pageNumber="326">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,278,1359,1384]" pageId="4" pageNumber="326">Definition.</emphasis>
Most members of this taxon have a regular anastomosing skeleton of polygonal meshes. Occasionally, some members exhibit a reduced anastomosed mesh restricted to the internal choanosome, or atrium wall, from which dendritic fibers depart towards the periphery of the body. Fibers are amber colored, with a laminated bark and dark granular pith. Tubular and massive lobular forms are frequent, but encrusting and stalked forms are also present. Their texture reflects the collagenous nature of the matrix. Pigmentation is frequently yellow or purple outside, and yellow or tan inside; however, greenish, violet, and pinkish colors may also be present, sometimes with a creamy or reddish purple tinge. The pigments oxidize rapidly in most species upon death or damage, to a deep purple or blue almost black. They produce bioactive compounds in the form of brominated tyrosine derivatives. Choanocyte chambers are diplodal, small, and spherical (amended from 
<bibRefCitation box="[1099,1372,1647,1672]" pageId="4" pageNumber="326" refId="ref8658" refString="Bergquist, P. R. &amp; Cook, S. D. C. (2002) Order Verongida Bergquist, 1978. In: Hooper, J. N. A. &amp; Van Soest, R. W. M. (Eds.), Systema Porifera: A guide to the classification of sponges. Fol. I. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers, New York, Boston, Dordrecht, London and Moscow, pp. 1081 - 1096. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4615 - 0747 - 5 _ 108" type="book chapter">Bergquist &amp; Cook 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="326" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1359,1781]" pageId="4" pageNumber="326">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1684,1709]" pageId="4" pageNumber="326">Remarks.</emphasis>
The definition of 
<bibRefCitation box="[539,841,1684,1709]" pageId="4" pageNumber="326" refId="ref8658" refString="Bergquist, P. R. &amp; Cook, S. D. C. (2002) Order Verongida Bergquist, 1978. In: Hooper, J. N. A. &amp; Van Soest, R. W. M. (Eds.), Systema Porifera: A guide to the classification of sponges. Fol. I. Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers, New York, Boston, Dordrecht, London and Moscow, pp. 1081 - 1096. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4615 - 0747 - 5 _ 108" type="book chapter">Bergquist &amp; Cook (2002)</bibRefCitation>
has been amended to permit inclusion of skeletal features observed in two new species reported below, which besides the typical reticulation of most 
<taxonomicName box="[1284,1382,1719,1744]" class="Demospongiae" family="Aplysinidae" genus="Aplysina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Verongiida" pageId="4" pageNumber="326" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1284,1382,1719,1744]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="326">Aplysina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp, still possess an outer dendritic skeleton connecting the deeper reticulated choanosome to the surface of the sponge.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
